{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c243f09d-3bf4-40f0-8d6c-a740fdbf212e","content":"The project doesn't exist yet in the current directory, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- Your C# server must read JSON-RPC messages from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout** (e.g., using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package with `AddStdioServerTransport()`).\n- For a published build, replace with `\"command\": \"path/to/MyMcpServer\"` for faster startup.\n\nAfter saving, open the **Command Palette** → **MCP: List Servers** to verify it's detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7583ab03-2d87-444f-98f3-10a2950948d2","outputTokens":306,"requestId":"D034:3509D7:15181D7:1793A39:6A0673BA"},"id":"53ee9b4c-5106-432d-8ef3-7310617e6589","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:15:46.520Z","parentId":"a28917ff-d591-400e-a170-a061ea7b96ee"}
